05133nam a22007695i 9781477322635DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20222021txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020034081  a97814773226357 a10.7560/3171812doi  a(DE-B1597)625666  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aHV6536.5.U6bM34 2021 4aHV6536.5b.M34 2021 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a364.152/3409732231 aMcGraw, Seamus, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom a Taller Tower :bThe Rise of the American Mass Shooter /cSeamus McGraw. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2022] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAuthor’s Note -- tPrologue. The Deepest Silence There Is -- tChapter 1 The Texas Sharpshooter Fallacy -- tChapter 2 Deliver Us from Evil -- tChapter 3 To Kill the Last Killer -- tChapter 4 “’Tis Not Alone My Inky Cloak ” -- tChapter 5 Jokers Wild -- tChapter 6 If You See Something, Say Something -- tChapter 7 A Good Guy with a Gun -- tChapter 8 I Cling to My Gun, You Cling to Yours -- tChapter 9 The Fog of War in Peacetime -- tChapter 10 From a Taller Tower -- tEpilogue. The Silence between Gunshots -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe, as a nation, have become desensitized to the shock and pain in the wake of mass shootings. In the bottomless silence between gunshots, as political stalemate ensures inaction, the killing continues; the dying continues. From a Taller Tower attends to the silence that has left us empty in the aftermath of these atrocities. Veteran journalist Seamus McGraw chronicles the rise of the mass shooter to dismantle the myths we have constructed around the murderers and ourselves. In 1966, America’s first mass shooter, from atop the University of Texas tower, unleashed a new reality: the fear that any of us may be targeted by a killer, and the complicity we bear in granting these murderers the fame or infamy they crave. Addressing individual cases in the epidemic that began in Austin, From a Taller Tower bluntly confronts our obsession with the shooters—and explores the isolation, narcissism, and sense of victimhood that fan their obsessions. Drawing on the experiences of survivors and first responders as well as the knowledge of mental health experts, McGraw challenges the notion of the “good guy with a gun,” the idolization of guns (including his own), and the reliability of traumatized memory. Yet in this terrible history, McGraw reminds us of the humanity that can stop the killing and the dying.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aMass shootingszUnited States. 0aMassacreszUnited States. 0aSchool shootingszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  agun violence, gun control, guns, mass shootings, mass shooting, school shootings, violence, gun rights, hate crimes, shooting, cultural history, communal violence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021z9783110753967oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074527640uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31718140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477322635423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477322635/original  a978-3-11-074527-6  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2